children.text: This is an interventional, 71 week, multi-centre, randomised, parallel-group, double-blind, placebo-controlled study. Approximately 330 participants with overweight or obesity, and type 2 diabetes (T2D), will be randomised in a 2:1 manner, to receive respectively either XXXXXXXXXX subcutaneously (s.c) 2.4 mg or placebo s.c. as an adjunct to lifestyle intervention counselling.

children.name: P[10]
children.text: The purpose of this study is to investigate the efficacy and safety of the amylin analogue, XXXXXXXXXX, as treatment for weight management in individuals living with overweight or obesity, and T2D. The study will compare the effect of once-weekly XXXXXXXXXX 2.4 mg versus placebo, administered (s.c.), on body weight reduction in participants with overweight or obesity, and T2D. The on-treatment, intervention, period is 64 weeks with a target maintenance dose of XXXXXXXXXX s.c. 2.4 mg. The results from a phase 2 study (NNXXX-XXX), showed that in participants with overweight or obesity and T2D, XXXXXXXXXX s.c. 2.4 mg provided a mean body weight reduction of approximately 8.1% after 32 weeks of treatment.1 The inclusion and exclusion criteria allow for enrolment of a diverse study population to reflect the target population of participants with obesity, or overweight and T2D. These participants represent a clinically relevant population for pharmacotherapeutic weight management, which are the co-primary endpoints in this study. The study is designed to also address and compare investigational medicinal product (IMP) safety, IMP tolerability, and participant well-being.

children.name: P[21]
children.text: The prevalence of obesity has increased over the last 30 years.3 In 2022 it was estimated that globally more than 1 billion people lived with obesity.4 Obesity is associated with an increased risk of developing health complications, such as type 2 diabetes (T2D),5, 6 dyslipidaemia, hypertension, cardiovascular (CV) disease7, obstructive sleep apnoea8, metabolic dysfunction-associated steatohepatitis (MASH)9, urinary incontinence10, several types of cancers,11, 12 and increased mortality.13-18

children.name: P[22]
children.text: The risk of obesity-related complications and comorbidities increases with increasing body mass index (BMI). A 5–10% reduction in body weight has significant health benefits in individuals with obesity in terms of reduced risk of developing T2D19 and CV death,20-22 as well as improving hypertension23, dyslipidaemia24, and MASH.25 In addition, improvements in patient-reported healthrelated quality of life, including physical function, have been demonstrated with body weight loss.26 Therefore, achieving and maintaining body weight loss in individuals with obesity is crucial to decrease the risk of and improve obesity-related complications.

children.name: P[23]
children.text: Lifestyle intervention is currently the first line treatment for obesity, however most people are not able to achieve and maintain a clinically relevant weight loss.27-30 Surgical interventions for weight loss offer an effective alternative for some people with obesity, but surgery carries a risk in connection with the procedure, and post-operative complications may occur31. Furthermore, surgery is limited in terms of the number of people it can be offered to, compared with the number of people requiring intervention to treat obesity. Pharmacotherapy may serve as an adjunct to lifestyle intervention to achieve and maintain a clinically relevant weight loss, to reduce the risk or severity of comorbid conditions, and to facilitate a healthier lifestyle. Few approved weight management medications are available and there is a need for effective therapeutic options with an alternative mode of action and differentiated benefits beyond weight loss.32-35

children.name: P[24]
children.text: Endogenous amylin is a neuroendocrine peptide hormone that is co-secreted with insulin by pancreatic beta-cells in response to food intake. It affects a number of gastrointestinal (GI) processes leading to delay of gastric emptying and suppression of post-prandial glucagon release.36 In addition, studies indicate that amylin is involved in the central regulation of food intake and body weight.37 XXXXXXXXXX (international non-proprietary name) is a long-acting amylin analogue with agonistic effects on amylin and calcitonin receptors.38

Safety and tolerability of XXXXXXXXXX s.c. 2.4 mg versus placebo will also be assessed.

children.text: For the evaluation of the efficacy of XXXXXXXXXX, two classes of estimands are defined. These estimands have different interpretation and are intended for different purposes.

children.name: P[31]
children.text: The first class of estimands (treatment policy estimands) address the policy of treatment for which the primary clinical question of interest is:

children.name: LBody
children.text: What is the difference in mean relative change in body weight from baseline to week 64 in participants with overweight or obesity, and T2D, regardless of adherence to randomised treatment or initiation of additional anti-obesity therapies (initiation or discontinuation of weight management drugs, initiation of weight management devices or weight loss surgery), where both XXXXXXXXXX and placebo are used as adjunct to lifestyle intervention counselling?

children.name: P[32]
children.text: The estimand is thus described by the following 5 attributes:

children.name: LBody
children.text: Population: participants with overweight or obesity, and T2D

children.name: LBody
children.text: Endpoints (co-primary): relative change in body weight from baseline to week 64 and achievement of ≥ 5% weight reduction from baseline to week 64

children.name: LBody
children.text: Treatment condition: randomised treatment regardless of adherence to treatment or initiation of additional anti-obesity therapies (initiation or discontinuation of weight management drugs, initiation of weight management devices or weight loss surgery)

children.name: LBody
children.text: Remaining intercurrent events: treatment discontinuation and additional anti-obesity therapies (initiation or discontinuation of weight management drugs, initiation of weight management devices or weight loss surgery) handled by a treatment policy strategy

children.name: LBody
children.text: Population-level summary: difference in mean changes between XXXXXXXXXX and placebo – relative change in body weight from baseline to week 64 and difference in proportion for achievement of ≥ 5% weight reduction from baseline to week 64.

children.name: P[33]
children.text: This estimand is expected to reflect the clinical practice scenario to the extent possible in a clinical study and considers both the efficacy and tolerability of XXXXXXXXXX.

children.name: P[34]
children.text: The second class of estimands (hypothetical estimands) addresses the treatment effect in the hypothetical scenario in which all participants remain on their randomised treatment without initiating additional anti-obesity therapies prior to the time of evaluation. The definition is identical to the definition above except the remaining intercurrent events (treatment discontinuation and additional anti-obesity therapies) are handled by a hypothetical strategy and the treatment condition is replaced by:

children.name: LBody
children.text: Treatment condition: randomised treatment regardless of changes in dose had all participants remained on randomised treatment without initiation of additional anti-obesity therapies.

children.name: P[35]
children.text: This estimand aims at addressing the treatment effect without the potential confounding effect of treatment discontinuation or additional anti-obesity therapies.

children.name: P[36]
children.text: For the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA), the primary statistical analysis for primary endpoint(s) will be based on the treatment policy estimand and for European Medicines Agency (EMA) and other countries, as well as for other purposes, the primary analysis will be based on the hypothetical estimand.

children.name: P[37]
children.text: Similar questions are of interest for the confirmatory secondary objectives. Thus, similar estimands are defined addressing these objectives for which the treatment comparison and/or endpoint of interest is substituted.

children.text: This is an interventional, multi-centre, randomised, parallel-group, double-blind, placebo-controlled study. Approximately 330 participants with overweight or obesity, and T2D, will be randomised in a 2:1 manner (see Figure 4-1), to receive either:

children.name: P[39]
children.text: Both treatments are administered once weekly with a pen-injector as an adjunct to lifestyle intervention counselling.

children.name: LBody
children.text: a 64-week intervention period which includes a 12-week dose escalation period followed by a 52-week maintenance period

children.name: LBody
children.text: The total duration of the study for each participant is approximately 71 weeks.

children.text: The once weekly XXXXXXXXXX treatment will be initiated at a dose of 0.5 mg. Following dose initiation, XXXXXXXXXX should be increased incrementally over a 12-week dose escalation period. The dose escalation should take place every 4 weeks, so that the dose is increased stepwise from 0.5 mg, to 1.0 mg, to 1.7 mg, until a target dose of 2.4 mg of XXXXXXXXXX is achieved, (see Figure 4-1). The placebo arm will run in parallel with the XXXXXXXXXX arm.

children.name: P[44]
children.text: Randomisation will be stratified according to treatment with GLP-1 containing medication and/or insulin medication (yes/yes, yes/no, no/yes, no/no). Up to 30% of the participants are allowed to be on either or both treatments at screening. That is, 70% of the participants should at screening not be treated with GLP-1 containing medication nor insulin. If the upper limit of 30% is reached, participants treated with GLP-1containing and/or insulin medication should not be screened for this study.

children.name: P[87]
children.text: Temporary discontinuation of study intervention should be considered for:

children.name: LBody
children.text: ALT or AST > 8 x upper limit of normal (ULN)

children.text: ALT or AST > 5 x ULN for more than 2 weeks

children.text: ALT (or AST) > 3 x ULN and total bilirubin > 2 x ULN (> 35% direct bilirubin) or ALT (or AST) > 3 x ULN and international normalised ratio (INR) > 1.5, which may indicate severe liver injury (potential Hy’s law)a

children.text: ALT (or AST) > 3 x ULN with the appearance of fatigue, nausea, vomiting, anorexia, abdominal pain or tenderness, fever, rash and/or eosinophilia (>5%).

These contact attempts must be documented in the participant’s source documents.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Should the participant continue to be unreachable, the participant will be considered to have withdrawn from the study with a primary reason of ‘lost to follow-up’ recorded in the end of study form.

children.name: P[104]
children.text: The following sections describe the assessments and procedures, while their timing is summarised in the SoA.

children.name: P[105]
children.text: Informed consent must be obtained before any study-related activity, see Appendix 1 (Section

children.name: P[106]
children.text: Adherence to the study design requirements, including those specified in the SoA is essential and required for study conduct.

children.name: P[107]
children.text: Assessments should be carried out according to the clinic’s standard of practice unless otherwise specified in the current section. Efforts should be made to limit the bias between assessments. The suggested order of the assessments at fasting site visits:

children.name: LBody
children.text: Blood sampling (not strictly required as first activity at non-fasting visits)

children.name: LBody
children.text: Patient-reported outcome (PRO) questionnaires in the order listed within the SoA (Section 1.2)

children.name: LBody
children.text: Performance outcomes (PerfO) (hand strength grip and sit to stand test)

children.name: P[108]
children.text: At fasting visits, participants should be encouraged to eat after blood sampling if needed. There should be a minimum of 30 minutes between eating and the assessment of vital signs, during which time the PRO questionnaires can be performed.

children.name: P[109]
children.text: Repeat samples may be taken for technical issues and unscheduled samples or assessments may be taken for safety reasons. Please refer to Appendix 2 (Section 9.6) for further details on laboratory samples.

children.name: P[110]
children.text: During the study selected data will be collected using electronic patient interaction device (ePID). The ePID consists of a participant mobile application pre-loaded on a study phone (eDiary) and a health care professional (HCP) web portal on a study tablet for sites. For information regarding the eDiary and HCP web portal please refer to the ePID site guide.

children.name: P[111]
children.text: At randomisation (V2), all participants will be provided with a study phone that must be used as an eDiary. The eDiary has been developed and will be maintained by Novo Nordisk. Before entering any study-related data, participants should receive training in eDiary use by the investigator or delegated site staff. The study phone should be returned at the end of study (V21).

children.name: P[112]
children.text: The eDiary must be used by the participant for the following data reporting:

children.name: LBody
children.text: Dosing diary including dose administered, date and time of IMP injection (Section Error! Reference source not found.)

children.name: LBody
children.text: PRO questionnaires (CoEQ, IWQOL-Lite-CT, SF-36v2® Acute and TFEQ-R18V2) (Section 8.2.3).

children.name: LBody
children.text: Participants eligible to take insulin as a concomitant medication (see section 5.1 and 5.2) should also report their pre-breakfast SMPG values (see Section 8.3.8)

children.name: P[114]
children.text: It is the responsibility of the investigator to instruct the participant about the timelines for completion of any data reporting in the eDiary. A paper back-up will be available at sites for cases where the participant has pending tasks to complete in the eDiary, or due to technical problems.

children.name: P[115]
children.text: The data reported by the participant in the eDiary must be reviewed by the investigator/site staff with the following frequency:

children.name: LBody
children.text: SMPG values must be reviewed by the investigator prior to each weekly contact (at site or by phone) with participants taking insulin as a concomitant medication, throughout the treatment period.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Dosing diary data entries must be reviewed at least every 10 days by investigator or delegated site staff.

children.name: LBody
children.text: All electronic hypoglycaemia diary data must be reviewed by the investigator at site visits, see SoA (Section 1.2), including confirmation that any reported level 3 hypoglycaemic episodes (see Appendix 7, Section 9.11) are reported accurately and confirmed by the participant.

children.name: LBody
children.text: If a participant fills in an entry in the electronic hypoglycaemia diary that indicates a severe hypoglycaemic episode (i.e. hypoglycaemia classification level 3, see Appendix 7 (Section 9.11)), this is considered potential SAE information and a notification for potential SAE reporting is sent to the site. Within 7 calendar days of receiving this potential SAE notification, the investigator must review the participant’s electronic hypoglycaemia diary and document the review accordingly.

children.name: LBody
children.text: If the electronic hypoglycaemia diary entry is evaluated by the investigator to be a SAE, reporting to Novo Nordisk must be performed according to the normal timelines for SAE reporting calculated from the day the investigator became aware of the SAE (Appendix 3, Section 9.7.5).

children.name: LBody
children.text: PRO questionnaires must be reviewed prior to each site visit, see SoA (Section 1.2).

children.name: P[116]
children.text: After reviewing, appropriate action described in the training material, should be taken in a timely manner and documented accordingly.

children.name: P[117]
children.text: Review of dosing diaries and PRO questionnaires in the HCP web portal (including CoEQ, IWQOL-Lite-CT, SF-36v2® Acute and TFEQ-R18V2 questionnaires), must be documented in the source documents or the participant’s medical record. In case of detection of an AE, this should be reported if applicable according to the protocol.

children.name: P[118]
children.text: If clarification of entries or discrepancies is needed in the eDiary, the participant must be consulted, and the outcome documented in the participant’s source documents. It is only the participant who should update data entered in the eDiary. Care must be taken not to bias the participant. If the participant cannot be consulted and/or the data in the eDiary remains uncorrected, this should be documented in the participant’s medical records or similar source documents. An audit trail will be maintained in ePID.

children.name: P[119]
children.text: A high-level data flow chart will be available in the data management plan outlining all systems used for data capture (e.g., eCRF, laboratory assessments, eCOA, ePID).

children.name: P[120]
children.text: The investigator will enter the participant’s prescribed IMP dose in the HCP portal. Site staff should change the participant’s status in the HCP portal if treatment with IMP is paused. Similarly, the status should be changed if IMP is resumed (Sections Error! Reference source not found. and 7.1).

children.name: P[121]
children.text: For Hungary and the UK: Please see country-specific requirements in Appendix 11 (Section Error! Reference source not found.).

children.name: P[122]
children.text: All screening evaluations must be completed and reviewed to confirm that potential participants meet all inclusion criteria and none of the exclusion criteria.

children.name: P[123]
children.text: The investigator will maintain a screening log to record details of all participants screened and rescreened and to confirm eligibility or record reason for screen failure, as applicable.

children.name: P[124]
children.text: At screening, participants will be provided with a card stating that they are participating in a study and giving contact details of relevant site staff that can be contacted in case of emergency.

children.name: P[125]
children.text: The term medical history covers medical events that the participant experienced prior to the time point from which AEs are collected.

children.name: P[126]
children.text: A concomitant illness is any illness that is already present at the time point from which AEs are collected or found as a result of a screening procedure or other study procedures performed before exposure to investigational intervention.

children.name: P[127]
children.text: In case of an abnormal and clinically significant finding fulfilling the definition of medical history or concomitant illness, the investigator must record the finding on the medical history/concomitant illness form in the eCRF.

children.name: P[128]
children.text: Information on hypoglycaemia unawareness will be recorded according to Clarke's questionnaire, question 8.45 The investigator must ask the participant in the following way: "To what extent can you tell by your symptoms that your blood glucose is low?" Participants answering ‘never, rarely or sometimes’ are considered to have impaired awareness of hypoglycaemia, whereas those answering ‘often or always’ are not.

children.name: P[129]
children.text: Medical history/concomitant illness includes but is not limited to a list of pre-specified disease classes in the eCRF. Relevant medical history/concomitant illness includes, but is not limited to, the following pre-specified disease classes:

children.name: P[130]
children.text: A lack of any records of the pre-specified medical history/concomitant illness is interpreted as if the participant did not have the condition at or before AE collection (exposure to the IMP).

children.name: P[131]
children.text: Information on relevant co-morbidities will be collected as part of medical history/concomitant illness at screening and baseline (V1 and V2) and a clinical evaluation of the status of selected comorbidities should be done at the end of treatment visit (V19) and documented in the Medical History Evaluation of Relevant Comorbidities eCRF.

children.name: P[132]
children.text: To be used in the overall safety evaluation of the IMP, the following must be documented at screening:

children.name: LBody
children.text: Risk factors for breast neoplasm (for female participants only), skin cancer and colon neoplasm, including both 1) family history of breast cancer, colon neoplasm and/or skin cancer in firstdegree relatives, age at time of diagnosis for relevant family members and 2) predisposing factors for breast and skin cancer, such as menarche/menopause, alcohol intake above the recommended local guidelines, hormone replacement therapy (HRT), sun exposure, light skin colour. Follow-up questions related to breast neoplasm (for female participants only) and colon neoplasm, will be asked at end of study.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Weight history (including previous weight, debut time of overweight, maximum weight, age at maximum weight, previous weight loss attempts, previous use of anti-obesity prescription medication, other methods to lose weight, considerations regarding bariatric surgery and overweight or obesity in first-degree relatives) must be documented at screening.

children.name: P[133]
children.text: Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) will be performed in a subgroup of approximately 80 participants in selected countries. The baseline MRI can be performed as soon as study eligibility (compliance with all inclusion and exclusion criteria) is documented and by the latest at V2 before initiating IMP (see Section 8.2.4).

children.name: P[134]
children.text: Planned time points for all efficacy assessments are provided in the SoA.

children.name: P[135]
children.text: All protocol-required laboratory assessments, as defined in Appendix 2 (Section 9.6), must be conducted in accordance with the SoA (Section 1.2) and the laboratory manual.

children.name: P[136]
children.text: Body weight must be measured without shoes, on an empty bladder and only wearing light clothing. Body weight should be measured on a digital scale and recorded in the eCRF in kilograms or pounds (one decimal) using the same scale throughout the study. The scale must be calibrated yearly as a minimum, unless the manufacturer or local requirements certifies that calibration of the scale is valid for the duration of the study.

children.name: P[137]
children.text: Height must be measured without shoes in centimetres (cm) or inches (one decimal). BMI will be calculated in the eCRF at each clinic visit based on height at screening and body weight at the clinic visit. BMI calculated in the eCRF at screening must comply with inclusion criterion number 4 (Section 5.1).

children.name: P[138]
children.text: Waist circumference is defined as the abdominal circumference located midway between the lower rib margin and the iliac crest. Measurements must be obtained in standing position with arms down their side and feet together. The tape should touch the skin but not compress soft tissue and twists in the tape should be avoided. The participants should be asked to breathe normally. A nonstretchable measuring tape will be provided by Novo Nordisk to ensure standardisation. Measurements must be recorded in the eCRF to nearest cm or inch.

children.name: P[139]
children.text: PRO questionnaires will be provided electronically to the participants in the eDiary. Through the HCP portal, the investigator or delegated site staff should push the questionnaires to the participant’s eDiary for completion according to the SoA (see Section 1.2). For information, please refer to the ePID site guide. Participants should complete the questionnaires at site. If the participant is unable to complete the questionnaires on the scheduled visit, the visit should be rescheduled within the visit window.

children.name: P[140]
children.text: Participants should be given the opportunity to complete the questionnaires by themselves without interruption.

children.name: P[141]
children.text: The following PRO measures will be used and are expected to take approximately 25 minutes in total, per visit, for the participants to complete:

children.name: H5[2]
children.text: Impact of Weight on Quality of Life-Lite Clinical Trials Version© (IWQOL-Lite-CT)46-48

children.name: LBody
children.text: IWQOL-Lite-CT measures weight-related physical and psychosocial functioning. The measure consists of 20 items yielding 3 composite scores, and 1 total score. Higher scores indicate better levels of functioning.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Composite scores (score range): Physical composite (0-100), Psychosocial composite (0-100), Physical Function composite (0-100).

children.name: LBody
children.text: Data collection mode: electronic (eDiary data entry performed at site)

children.name: LBody
children.text: The SF-36v2® Acute measures Health-Related Quality of Life (HRQOL). The measure consists of 36 items yielding 8 health domain scores and 2 component summary scores. SF-36v2® Acute scores are norm-based scores, i.e. transformed to a scale where the 2009 US general population has a mean of 50 and a standard deviation of 10.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Health domain scores (score range): Physical Functioning (19.0 to 57.6), Role limitation due to physical health problems (Role-Physical) (21.9 to 57.1), Bodily Pain (21.4 to 60.9), General Health (21.3 to 65.4), Social Functioning (17.2 to 56.7), Role limitation due to emotional problems (Role-Emotional) (9.8 to 55.6), Vitality (25.6 to 69.1), Mental Health (13.1 to 62.7).

children.name: LBody
children.text: Component summary scores (score range): Physical Component Summary (6.1 to 79.7), Mental Component Summary (-3.8 to 78.7)

children.name: LBody
children.text: Data collection mode: electronic (eDiary data entry performed at site)

children.name: LBody
children.text: CoEQ is a 19-item multidimensional PRO that assesses the experience of hunger, satiety, and severity and type of food cravings.

children.name: LBody
children.text: CoEQ consists of 4 subscales that measure craving control (5 items), positive mood (4 items), craving for sweet (4 items), and craving for savoury food (4 items), and 2 single items that address hunger and satiety. Each item is evaluated on a 0-10 (i.e., 11-point) numeric rating scale.

children.name: LBody
children.text: The total score for each subscale is calculated as the sum of the item scores divided by the number of items in the subscale. Scores ranges are thus: Craving Control (0-50/5 = 0-10); Positive Mood (0-40/4 = 0-10); Craving Sweet (0-40/4 = 0-10); Craving Savoury food (0-40/4 = 0-10); single items that address hunger and satiety (0-10).

children.name: LBody
children.text: For the Positive Mood subscale, item 6 ‘How anxious have you felt?’ is reversed. For the Craving Control subscale, the subscale score is reversed so that a higher score represents a greater level of Craving Control.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Data collection mode: electronic (eDiary data entry performed at site)

children.name: H5[5]
children.text: Three factor eating questionnaire revised 18-item version 2 (TFEQ-R18V2)52, 53

children.name: LBody
children.text: TFEQ-R18V2 was developed to assess eating behaviour in people with obesity and people without obesity in epidemiological studies and clinical studies. It includes 18 items which are aggregated to 3 separate scales: cognitive restraint, uncontrolled eating, and emotional eating.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Higher scores indicate more uncontrolled, restrained, and emotional eating.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Data collection mode: electronic (eDiary data entry performed at site)

children.name: P[142]
children.text: In relation to each study visit, the investigator should review the data to ensure completeness and acknowledge the review in the HCP portal (see additional details in Section 8). If any AEs are identified when reviewing the responses, AEs should be reported in accordance with Section 8.4 and Appendix 3 (Section 9.7).

children.name: P[143]
children.text: The following performance outcomes (PerfO) assessments will be used:

children.name: LBody
children.text: The hand grip strength test measures the muscular strength (maximum force) generated by the forearm muscles. The primary outcome is the maximum grip strength in kg (the best of six measurements alternating between the two hands).

children.name: LBody
children.text: The hand grip strength test should be measured using a hydraulic hand dynamometer, the same hand dynamometer should be used throughout the study. The test should be performed on both hands. For each participant hand dominance and test results to the nearest kilogram should be recorded in the eCRF.

children.name: LBody
children.text: The hand grip strength test must be performed according to the manual.

children.name: LBody
children.text: The sit-to-stand test is a 30 second test used to assess participant leg strength and endurance. Participants are instructed to perform as many full sit-to-stand cycles as possible within 30 seconds. The primary outcome is the total count of full sit-to-stand repetitions completed in 30 seconds which should be recorded in the eCRF.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Sit-to-stand test must be performed according to the manual.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Participants with permanent physical limitations not related to obesity e.g. quadriplegia, that in the investigator’s opinion prevent them from being able to complete the assessment, should be exempt from the assessment. The rationale for exemption should be documented in the eCRF sit to stand form as ‘due to physical limitations’. The participant should not be assessed at future visits.

children.name: ParagraphSpan
children.text: MRI is expected to be performed in a subgroup of approximately 80 participants in Argentina, Canada, Czechia, Hungary, Romania and the US. At selected MRI units, participants will have 3 MRI scans taken of their upper abdomen and thigh to measure changes in abdominal, thigh, and total muscle and fat volumes and ectopic fat content. The participant must consent to the MRI procedure and image analysis communicated in the main informed consent form, before any scan is performed. The first (baseline) MRI scan should be performed prior to IMP. This MRI can be performed as soon as study eligibility (compliance with all inclusion and exclusion criteria) is documented in the medical records and at the latest, randomisation. The MRI scan during dose

children.name: ParagraphSpan[2]
children.text: maintenance can be performed up to 7 days before, or after, the scheduled visit. The MRI scan at the end of treatment can be performed up to 7 days before the scheduled visit.

children.name: P[145]
children.text: The investigator must ensure that a standard radiology assessment of the magnetic resonance images is performed by a qualified radiologist. In case of any incidental findings from the baseline MRI, these findings must be recorded as medical history, and continuation or discontinuation of study participants must be considered by the investigator. In case of incidental findings from the MRI scans performed after baseline, the investigator must assess if any adverse event reporting is required (see Section 8.4). It is the responsibility of the investigator to refer the participant for further examination and treatment as needed.

children.name: P[146]
children.text: All equipment will be calibrated according to the vendor’s procedures and guidelines.

children.name: P[147]
children.text: Images will be analysed by a centralised imaging core laboratory and Novo Nordisk. Information about the processing and analysis of the magnetic resonance images/data will be described in documents prepared by the imaging core laboratory. Raw images, results, artifacts, and manual annotations from the imaging analyses will be electronically transferred directly from the centralised imaging core laboratory to Novo Nordisk.

children.name: P[148]
children.text: To test the MRI protocol, the imaging core laboratory may perform test scans in healthy volunteers or on phantoms. This test will check the MRI settings and the quality of the images generated. MRI facilities may follow local ethical approval practice for handling and consenting healthy volunteers. Novo Nordisk will not have access to any data generated from MRI examination on healthy volunteers and these subjects are therefore not considered part of the study.

children.name: P[149]
children.text: Medical MRI images collected from participants during the study, as described in Section 8.2.4 and in the imaging manual provided by the imaging CRO, will be used for exploratory research to better understand obesity risks and comorbidities, and impact of XXXXXXXXXX on adipose tissue and lean muscle distribution and body composition. Potential additional analyses and measurements from the images will be described in a separate ‘Image Analysis Plan’, which will be completed before CSR. The results from the exploratory imaging analyses will not be part of the CSR. The exploratory image analysis is for research and hypothesis generation. No clinical decisions can be made based on exploratory data.

children.name: P[150]
children.text: Planned time points for all safety assessments are provided in the SoA.

children.name: P[151]
children.text: A physical examination will include assessments of:

children.name: LBody
children.text: Head, ears, eyes, nose, mouth, throat, neck

children.name: P[152]
children.text: Body measurements (e.g., height and weight) will also be measured and recorded as specified in the SoA.

children.name: P[153]
children.text: Investigators should pay special attention to clinical signs related to previous serious illnesses.

children.name: P[154]
children.text: Pulse rate as well as systolic blood pressure (SBP) and diastolic blood pressure (DBP) will be assessed as per the SoA (Section 1.2).

children.name: P[155]
children.text: Blood pressure and pulse rate measurements will be preceded by at least 5 minutes of rest for the participant in a quiet setting without distractions (e.g., no use of television, cell phones). The participant should avoid caffeine and smoking at least 30 minutes prior to measuring the blood pressure.

children.name: P[156]
children.text: Blood pressure and pulse rate measurements will be assessed sitting with a completely automated device. Manual techniques must be used only if an automated device is not available.

children.name: P[157]
children.text: Blood pressure will consist of 3 systolic and diastolic blood pressure measurements with intervals of at least 1-2 minutes. An additional fourth blood pressure measurement must be performed if the first two readings on systolic or diastolic blood pressure differ by >10 mmHg. No more than four measurements will be performed.

children.name: LBody
children.text: The mean systolic blood pressure and diastolic blood pressure values are calculated based on the last 2 measurements.

children.name: LBody
children.text: The last 2 systolic and last 2 diastolic blood pressure measurements will be recorded in the eCRF.

children.name: P[158]
children.text: Pulse rate will be measured in connection to the blood pressure measurements.

children.name: LBody
children.text: The mean pulse rate value is calculated based on the last 2 pulse rate measurements.

children.name: LBody
children.text: The pulse rate for the last 2 measurements will be recorded in the eCRF.

children.name: P[159]
children.text: On fasting visits, participants should be encouraged to eat after blood sampling. There should be a minimum of 30 minutes between eating and assessment of vital signs, during which time the COAs can be performed.

children.name: P[160]
children.text: An eye exam will only be performed at screening for participants who have not had an eye examination within 90 days of screening.

children.name: P[161]
children.text: Participants with uncontrolled and potentially unstable diabetic retinopathy or maculopathy are not eligible as this indicates retinopathy that has recently progressed to a level that requires intervention or is approaching intervention but has yet to be brought under control.

children.name: ParagraphSpan
children.text: Results of an eye examination performed by an ophthalmologist or another suitably qualified health care provider (e.g., optometrist) possibly aided by diagnostic artificial intelligence algorithms

children.name: ParagraphSpan[2]
children.text: approved by FDA and/or CE-marked must be available and evaluated by the investigator before randomisation to assess eligibility. The eye examination must be performed as a fundus photography (e.g., 3-field 45 degree, 2-field 60 degree or better, colour or red-free) or by slit-lamp biomicroscopy examination (e.g., using a pre-corneal or corneal contact lens examination). The use of 3 fields of 45 degree diameters, one fovea-centered, one disc-centered and one at a comparable distance temporal of the fovea, is a good substitute for two 60 degree fields. In addition, an Optical Coherence Tomography (OCT) must be performed. Pharmacological pupil-dilation is a requirement unless using a digital fundus photography camera specified for non-dilated examination. If diagnostic artificial intelligence algorithms are used an additional eye examination may be necessary if indicated so by the algorithm.

children.name: P[163]
children.text: If the participant had such an eye examination performed within 90 days prior to screening, the investigator may base his/her evaluation upon the results of that examination. The examination must be repeated before randomisation if the participant has experienced worsening of visual function since the last examination. If the applicable eye examination was performed before the participant signed the informed consent form, it must be documented that the reason for performing the examination was not related to this study.

children.name: P[164]
children.text: After randomisation an eye examination must be performed according to above as per protocol SoA. The investigator will indicate the outcome of each eye examination.

children.name: P[165]
children.text: 12-lead ECG will be obtained as outlined in the SoA using an ECG machine that automatically calculates the heart rate and measures PR, QRS, QT and QTc intervals.

children.name: P[166]
children.text: ECG must be performed at screening (V1) and during the study when deemed necessary by the Investigator, according to the manual from the supplier.

children.name: P[167]
children.text: Results of the ECG should be available and evaluated by the investigator before randomisation (V2).

children.name: P[168]
children.text: All protocol-required laboratory assessments, as defined in Appendix 2 (Section 9.6), must be conducted in accordance with the SoA (Section 1.2) and the laboratory manual.

children.name: P[169]
children.text: Safety questionnaires will be provided on paper and are to be completed at site visits in accordance with the SoA (Section 1.2). If the participant is unable to complete the questionnaires on the scheduled visit, the visit should be rescheduled within the visit window.

children.name: P[170]
children.text: The following questionnaires will be used and are expected to take approximately 15 minutes in total, per visit, for the participants to complete:

children.name: H5[9]
children.text: Columbia-Suicide Severity Rating Scale (C-SSRS) (baseline and since last visit)54, 55

children.name: LBody
children.text: C-SSRS is a detailed, binary response questionnaire assessing both suicidal behaviour and suicidal ideation. In cases where responses are ‘Yes’, follow-up inquiries are used to obtain additional information on suicidal ideation and behaviour.

children.name: LBody
children.text: The investigator or qualified delegate must complete sufficient training prior to conducting the C-SSRS questionnaire interview

children.name: LBody
children.text: PHQ-9 is a 9-item depression module of the patient health questionnaire, which is a self-administered diagnostic tool used for assessment of mental disorders.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Participants should be given the opportunity to complete the questionnaire by themselves without interruption.

children.name: P[171]
children.text: If a participant has a PHQ-9 score of 10-14 (both inclusive), the participant should be referred to a Mental Health Professional (MHP) if judged relevant by the investigator. If referral is not deemed relevant this along with the reason why must be documented.

children.name: P[172]
children.text: A participant must be referred to a MHP if:

children.name: LBody
children.text: the participant has a PHQ-9 score ≥15 or

children.name: LBody
children.text: the participant has any suicidal behaviour or

children.name: LBody
children.text: the participant has any suicidal ideation of type 4 or type 5 on any C-SSRS assessment or

children.name: LBody
children.text: in the opinion of the investigator, it is necessary for the safety of the participant.

children.name: P[173]
children.text: If one or more of the referral criteria are met, the investigator should explain to the participant why the referral and psychiatric evaluation by a MHP is needed. If the participant refuses to be referred to an MHP, the participant’s decision should be documented and the investigator must assess if it is safe for the participant to continue in the study or if the participant should be discontinued from IMP.

children.name: P[174]
children.text: If a participant’s psychiatric disorder can be adequately treated with psychotherapy and/or pharmacotherapeutic treatment, then the participant, at the discretion of the investigator (and in agreement with the MHP), may continue in the study. Otherwise, the participant must be discontinued from IMP due to safety concern as judged by the investigator.

children.name: P[175]
children.text: Women of childbearing potential (WOCBP) will only be included after a negative, highly sensitive urine pregnancy test (refer to Appendix 2 (Section 9.6)) at screening and at randomisation.

children.name: P[176]
children.text: WOCBP must perform urine pregnancy tests at all site visits as well as at remote visits as outlined in the SoA (Section 1.2). The participants will be provided with urine pregnancy tests for remote testing. The participants should be instructed by site staff in correct use of the tests.

children.name: ParagraphSpan
children.text: Pregnancy testing will be performed whenever a menstruation is missed or late or when pregnancy is otherwise suspected. IMP must be discontinued until a pregnancy test has been confirmed

children.name: ParagraphSpan[2]
children.text: negative by the investigator (see Section 7.1) for information on discontinuation and restarting of IMP).

children.name: P[178]
children.text: Additional pregnancy testing will be performed during the treatment period, if required locally, refer to Appendix 11 (Section Error! Reference source not found.).

children.name: P[179]
children.text: At each site visit, until end of treatment, WOCBP must receive contraceptive counselling to ensure effective contraception. The contraceptive counselling, the contraceptive method and the result of the pregnancy test must be documented.

children.name: P[180]
children.text: All participants should be instructed on how to measure their SMPG. The investigator should throughout the study ensure that the participant is able to correctly measure their PG at any time. At randomisation (V2), participants will be provided with a blood glucose (BG) meter. The BG meter provided by Novo Nordisk should be used for the measurements required in the protocol. All BG meters provided by Novo Nordisk will be compliant with safety, health, and environmental protection requirements of the country they are provided in, e.g., BG meters in the EU/EEA will be CE-marked.

children.name: P[181]
children.text: When using BG meters, the measurement is performed with capillary blood calibrated to plasma equivalent glucose values, i.e., the measurement is performed on blood while the value is reported as plasma; therefore ‘PG’ or ‘self-measured plasma glucose’ (SMPG) are the terms to use as descriptor for the value.

children.name: P[182]
children.text: The BG meters use test strips calibrated to plasma values. Therefore, all measurements performed with capillary blood are automatically calibrated to plasma equivalent glucose values, which will be shown on the display.

children.name: P[183]
children.text: If a hypoglycaemic episode is suspected, or if the measurement indicates a hypoglycaemic episode, see Appendix 7 (Section 9.11) for information on further measurements and reporting of hypoglycaemic episodes.

children.text: All AEs and SAEs must be collected from first administration of investigational intervention and until the end of study visit (21) in accordance with the SoA (Section 1.2) or whenever, within the above time period, the site becomes aware of an AE or SAE.

children.name: P[197]
children.text: AE and SAE reporting timelines can be found in Appendix 3 (Section 9.7). All SAEs must be recorded and reported to Novo Nordisk or designee without undue delay but not later than within 24 hours of obtaining knowledge of the events. Similarly, the investigator must submit any updated data on SAEs that could have led to an SAE to Novo Nordisk or designee without undue delay, but not later than within 24 hours of obtaining knowledge of the information.

children.name: P[198]
children.text: Investigators are not obligated to actively seek for AEs or SAEs in former study participants. However, if the investigator learns of any SAE with a suspected causal relationship to the IMP or to study participation, occurring after a participant has discontinued/completed the study, the investigator must notify Novo Nordisk without undue delay.

children.name: P[199]
children.text: The investigator must promptly notify Novo Nordisk by reporting the SAE in EDC or completing a paper AE form and Safety Information Form as described in Appendix 3 (Section 9.7).

children.name: P[200]

children.name: P[201]
children.text: The method of recording, evaluating and assessing causality of AEs and SAEs and the procedures for completing and transmitting reports on SAEs are provided in Appendix 3 (Section 9.7).

children.name: P[202]
children.text: Care should be taken not to introduce bias when detecting AEs and/or SAEs. Open-ended and nonleading verbal questioning of the participant is the preferred method to inquire about events.

children.name: P[203]
children.text: After the initial AE report, the investigator is required to proactively follow each participant at subsequent visits/contacts. All SAEs should be followed until the outcome of the event is final or until the participant is lost to follow-up as described in Section 7.3. Further information on followup and outcome of AEs is given in Appendix 3 (Section 9.7).

children.name: P[204]
children.text: Prompt notification by the investigator to Novo Nordisk or designee of an SAE is essential so that legal obligations and ethical responsibilities towards the safety of participants and the safety of an investigational intervention are met.

children.name: ParagraphSpan

children.text: the regulatory authority, IRB/IEC and investigators. This also includes suspected unexpected serious adverse reactions (SUSARs).

children.name: P[206]

children.text: If suspicion of a hypersensitivity reaction occurs, the participants should be instructed to contact the site staff as soon as possible for further guidance.

children.text: The primary statistical analysis will be linear regression using an analysis of covariance model (ANCOVA) using multiple imputation to handle missing data assuming that the missing data mechanism is missing at random (MAR) within the groups used for imputation. Imputation of missing week 64 data will be done within 4 groups of participants defined by treatment arm and treatment status at time of evaluation (i.e., whether participants at time of evaluation (i) are still on study treatment and have not initiated additional anti-obesity therapies or (ii) have discontinued study treatment and/or initiated additional anti-obesity therapies). children.text: Analysis model: The 1000 complete data sets will be analysed separately using an ANCOVA with treatment arm and GLP-1 and/or insulin user (yes/yes, yes/no, no/yes, no/no) stratum as a factor and baseline body weight as covariate. children.text: Analysis model: The 1000 complete data sets will be analysed separately.

children.name: P[303]
children.text: A logistic regression model with treatment arm as factor and baseline body weight as covariate will be fitted to the observed and imputed data.

children.name: P[304]
children.text: The results from the logistic regression model will be used to predict the probability of achieving the responder endpoint for all participants had they (counterfactually) been assigned to each specific treatment.

children.name: P[305]
children.text: Average treatment difference (TD) in probability will be estimated by subtracting the average predicted probabilities and the corresponding standard errors will be calculated using the deltamethod.

children.name: P[306]
children.text: The results obtained from analysing the individual data sets will be combined using Rubin’s rule to draw inference.

children.name: P[307]
children.text: For the hypothetical estimand, the MMRM analysis will be implemented in a sequential imputation framework.

children.name: P[308]
children.text: In line with ICH E9 (R1),59 sensitivity analyses will be performed investigating the robustness of the conclusions made on the basis of the primary analyses towards the impact of missing data.

children.name: P[309]
children.text: Jump to reference multiple imputation approach (J2R-MI):

children.name: P[310]
children.text: This unconditional imputation approach addresses the sensitivity of the MAR assumption by assuming that participants instantly after discontinuation lose any effect of randomised treatment.60 Missing values of body weight at week 64 for all treatment groups are imputed by sampling among all available assessments at week 64 in the placebo group. The multiple imputation approach is done as above with the first step replaced by:

children.name: P[311]
children.text: Imputation: Defines an imputation model using placebo participants from FAS with a week 64 measurement. The model will be a linear regression of body weight (kg) at week 64 with GLP-1 and/or insulin user (yes/yes, yes/no, no/yes, no/no) stratum as factor and baseline body weight (kg) as covariate. No interactions will be included. The estimated posterior distribution for the parameters (regression coefficients and variances) in the imputation models are then used to impute missing week 64 body weight values for each randomised treatment arm. This will be done 1000 times and results in 1000 complete data sets.

children.name: P[313]
children.text: This sensitivity analysis for relative change in body weight evaluates the robustness of the superiority conclusions to violations of the MAR assumption. First, missing body weight data are imputed according to the primary multiple imputation approach. Then, a penalty is added to the imputed values at week 64. The approach is to explore a range of penalties for both treatment arms, and the impact these would have on the study conclusions. A two-dimensional space of penalties will be explored for the two treatment arms.

children.name: P[315]
children.text: An analysis using non-retrieved participants as non-responders in the logistic regression analysis will be done in order to assess the sensitivity of the MAR assumption on the conclusion.

children.name: P[317]
children.text: The continuous confirmatory secondary endpoints will be analysed using the same analysis and imputation models as used to address the primary estimands for the continuous primary endpoint and also the same sensitivity analyses will be done except for the tipping point analysis which will not be done for confirmatory secondary endpoints. For secondary weight loss responder endpoints, the model is similar to that of the 5% weight loss responder endpoint.

children.name: P[318]
children.text: For details on analyses of additional supportive secondary endpoints, please refer to the SAP.

children.text: Population PK analysis based on the XXXXXXXXXX concentration data from the study will be performed.

children.text: The objective of the population PK analysis is to evaluate the effects of pre-specified covariates on XXXXXXXXXX exposure. A more technical and detailed elaboration of the population PK analysis will be given in a modelling analysis plan (MAP), which will be prepared before DBL.

children.name: P[326]
children.text: Calculation of power is based on the treatment policy estimand, as this is expected to be conservative compared to the hypothetical estimand. For the present sample size calculation, up to 30% of participants are allowed on GLP-1 treatment with an assumed TD on weight loss to placebo of 3%. At the same time, 70% of participants will be non-GLP-1 users with an assumed TD of 8% on weight loss. This corresponds to adjusted mean for the pooled population of 6.5% in weight loss and standard deviation (SD) of 10.

children.text: 9.7 Appendix 3: Adverse Events and Serious Adverse Events: Definitions and procedures for recording, evaluating, follow-up and reporting

children.name: P[342]
children.text: An AE is any untoward medical occurrence in a clinical study participant that is temporally associated with the use of IMP, whether or not considered related to the IMP. An AE can therefore be any unfavourable and unintended sign (including an abnormal laboratory finding), symptom or disease (new or exacerbated) temporally associated with the use of an IMP.

children.name: H4[31]
children.text: Events to be reported as AEs:

children.name: P[343]
children.text: In addition to events falling under the AE definition above, the following are examples of events that also are to be reported as AEs:

children.name: LBody
children.text: Any abnormal laboratory test results or safety assessments considered clinically significant in the medical and scientific judgment of the investigator, including events that have worsened from prior to the time point from which AEs are collected.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Conditions detected or diagnosed after IMP administration even though it may have been present prior to the time point from which AEs are collected.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Exacerbation/worsening of a chronic or intermittent condition including either an increase in frequency and/or intensity of the condition.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Signs, symptoms or the clinical sequelae of a suspected drug–drug interaction.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Signs, symptoms or the clinical sequelae of a suspected overdose of IMP regardless of intent.

children.name: P[344]
children.text: A ‘lack of efficacy’ or ‘failure of expected pharmacological action’ per se will not be reported as an AE or SAE. Such instances will be captured in the efficacy assessments. However, the signs, symptoms and/or clinical sequelae resulting from lack of efficacy will be reported as AE or SAE if they fulfil the definition.

children.name: P[345]
children.text: Events NOT to be reported as AEs:

children.name: LBody
children.text: Conditions present prior to the time point from which AEs are collected and anticipated day-today fluctuations of these conditions. Record such conditions as concomitant illness/medical history.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Medical or surgical procedures (e.g., endoscopy, appendectomy). The condition that leads to the procedure is the AE.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Medical or surgical procedures not preceded by an AE or worsening of a known condition.

children.name: P[346]
children.text: An SAE is an AE that fulfils at least one of the following criteria:

children.name: LBody
children.text: The term ‘life-threatening’ refers to an event in which the participant was at risk of death at the time of the event. It does not refer to an event which hypothetically might have caused death, if it were more severe.

children.name: ParagraphSpan
children.text: Requires inpatient hospitalisation or prolongation of existing hospitalisation

children.name: ParagraphSpan
children.text: Hospitalisation signifies that the participant has been admitted at the hospital or emergency ward for observation and/or treatment that would not have been appropriate in the

children.name: ParagraphSpan[2]
children.text: physician’s office or outpatient setting. Complications that occur during hospitalisation are AEs. If a complication prolongs hospitalisation or fulfils any other seriousness criteria, the event is serious. When in doubt as to whether ‘hospitalisation’ occurred or was necessary, the AE should be considered serious.

children.name: ParagraphSpan
children.text: Hospitalisation for elective treatment (e.g., elective medical or surgical procedures) of a condition that was present prior to the time point from which AEs are collected and that did not worsen, is not considered an AE.

children.name: P
children.text: Note: Hospitalisations for administrative, study-related, social and convenience reasons do not constitute AEs and should therefore not be reported as AEs or SAEs. Hospital admissions for medical or surgical procedures, planned before study inclusion, are not considered AEs or SAEs.

children.name: P[347]
children.text: • Results in persistent or significant disability/incapacity

children.name: LBody
children.text: The term ‘disability’ means a substantial disruption of a person’s ability to conduct normal life functions. This definition is not intended to include experience of relatively minor medical significance, such as uncomplicated headache, nausea, vomiting, diarrhoea, influenza, and accidental trauma (e.g., sprained ankle), that may interfere with or prevent everyday life functions but do not constitute a substantial disruption. • Is a congenital anomaly/birth defect

children.name: LBody
children.text: Medical or scientific judgment should be exercised by the investigator in deciding whether SAE reporting is appropriate in other situations. This includes important medical events that may not be immediately life-threatening or result in death or hospitalisation but may jeopardise the participant or may require medical or surgical intervention to prevent one of the other outcomes listed in the above definition. These events should usually be considered serious and reported as SAEs using the important medical event criterion.

children.name: ParagraphSpan
children.text: The following must be reported as an SAE using the important medical event criterion if no other seriousness criteria are applicable:

children.name: LBody
children.text: Suspicion of transmission of infectious agents via IMP

children.name: LBody
children.text: Risk of liver injury defined as alanine aminotransferase (ALT) or aspartate aminotransferase (AST) >3x ULN and total bilirubin >2x ULN where no alternative aetiology exists (Hy’s law)

children.name: H4[32]

children.name: P[348]
children.text: A specific event form needs to be completed for the following events.

children.name: P[349]
children.text: Events of symptomatic acute gallbladder disease (including gallstones and cholecystitis).

children.name: P[350]
children.text: The diagnosis of acute pancreatitis requires two of the following three features:

children.name: LBody
children.text: abdominal pain consistent with pancreatitis (onset of a persistent, severe, epigastric pain often radiating to the back)

children.name: LBody
children.text: serum lipase activity (and/or amylase activity) at least three times greater than the upper limit of normal

children.name: LBody
children.text: characteristic findings of pancreatitis on imaging.

children.name: P[351]
children.text: New onset or worsening of diabetic retinopathy and/or diabetic macular oedema.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Any disorders of the liver including cholestatic conditions and liver related signs and symptoms

children.name: LBody
children.text: If a liver related AE is reported, the Hepatic Event form must be filled out. For suggested actions and follow-up assessments for selected hepatic events; see Appendix 5 (Section 9.9).

children.name: P[352]
children.text: For all types of hypersensitivity reactions, additional information need to be collected including information about the type of reaction and signs and symptoms associated with the event. In case of systemic hypersensitivity reactions relevant immunological tests should be performed (please refer to Section 8.9.2).

children.name: P[353]
children.text: For all types of injection site reactions additional information needs to be collected including information about the objective findings (e.g. erythema, haematoma, ecchymosis) and local symptoms (e.g. burning, pain, numbness, itching)

children.name: P[354]
children.text: In case of recurrent episodes of injection site reactions, these can be reported as one ongoing adverse event of recurrent injection site reaction. In this case, only one adverse event form needs to be filled in but every episode should be captured in an event specific form.

children.name: P[355]
children.text: A medication error is an unintended failure in the IMP treatment process that leads to, or has the potential to lead to, harm to the participant, such as:

children.name: LBody
children.text: administration of wrong drug and/or use of wrong device Note: Use of wrong Kit ID/DUN is not considered a medication error unless it results in administration of wrong drug.

children.name: LBody
children.text: wrong route of administration, such as intramuscular instead of subcutaneous.

children.name: LBody
children.text: accidental administration of a higher dose than intended. The administered dose must deviate from the intended dose to an extent where clinical consequences for the study participant were likely to happen as judged by the investigator, although they did not necessarily occur.

children.name: P[356]
children.text: Missed doses or discontinuation of IMP (temporarily or permanently) are not to be reported as medication errors.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Situations where the IMP is intentionally and inappropriately used not in accordance with the protocol (e.g., overdose to maximise effect)

children.name: LBody
children.text: Persistent or sporadic, intentional excessive use of an IMP which is accompanied by harmful physical or psychological effects (e.g., overdose with the intention to cause harm)

children.name: P[357]
children.text: Note: Medication error, misuse and abuse must always be reported on an AE form and the specific event form must be completed. The AE diagnosis on the AE form must reflect what occurred (e.g., accidental overdose, intentional overdose or other). If the medication error and/or misuse and abuse resulted in a clinical consequence, this must be reported on an additional AE form.

children.name: P[358]
children.text: All neoplasms (both malignant and non-malignant) confirmed by histopathology or other substantial clinical evidence. To assess a participant’s risk of a developing neoplasm, family history of neoplasms will also be collected.

children.name: H4[42]
children.text: Other events requiring collection of additional information

children.name: P[359]
children.text: All hypoglycaemic episodes must be recorded on a hypoglycaemic episode form (see Appendix 7 (Section 9.11)). If the hypoglycaemic episode fulfils the criteria for an SAE, then in addition to the hypoglycaemic episode form, an AE form and a safety information form must be filled in. One AE form and safety information form can cover several hypoglycaemic episode forms, if the participant has not recovered between the episodes.

children.name: P[360]
children.text: In all cases where one or more results from liver laboratory parameters (ALT, AST or ALP) measured in a blood sample at the central laboratory are increased above the limits defined below, the Elevated Liver Enzymes form must be completed. Criteria for discontinuation of study intervention may also apply; see Section 7.1.1.1.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Alanine aminotransferase (ALT): >3.0 x ULN if baseline was normal; >3.0 x above baseline if baseline was abnormal

children.name: LBody
children.text: Aspartate aminotransferase (AST): >3.0 x ULN if baseline was normal; >3.0 x above baseline if baseline was abnormal

children.name: LBody
children.text: Alkaline phosphatase (ALP): >2.5 x ULN if baseline was normal; >2.5 x above baseline if baseline was abnormal

children.name: P[361]
children.text: For suggested actions and follow-up assessments for selected hepatic events, see Appendix 5 (Section 9.9).

children.name: H3[41]
children.text: 9.7.4 Recording and follow-up of AEs and/or SAEs

children.name: P[362]
children.text: The investigator will record all relevant information about AEs/SAEs in the CRF.

children.name: P[363]
children.text: The investigator will attempt to establish a diagnosis of the event based on signs, symptoms and/or other clinical information. In such cases, the diagnosis (not the individual signs/symptoms) will be documented as the AE/SAE.

children.name: P[364]
children.text: When an AE/SAE occurs, it is the responsibility of the investigator to review all documentation (e.g., hospital progress notes, laboratory and diagnostics reports) related to the event.

children.name: P[365]
children.text: There may be instances when copies of source documents (e.g., medical records) for certain cases are requested by Novo Nordisk. In such cases, all participant identifiers, with the exception of the subject ID, must be redacted on the copies of the source documents before submission to Novo Nordisk, see Section Error! Reference source not found..

children.name: P[366]
children.text: Please refer to Figure 9-2 for reporting of non-serious AEs. For all non-serious AEs, the applicable forms should be signed when the event is resolved or at the end of the study at the latest. For signoff of SAE-related forms, refer to Section 9.7.5.

children.name: P[367]
children.text: If an SAE is considered to have a causal relationship with a concomitant medication it is important that the suspected relationship is reported to Novo Nordisk in e.g., the alternative aetiology section on the safety information form. Novo Nordisk may need to report it to relevant regulatory authorities.

children.name: P[368]
children.text: If an SAE is a suspected drug – drug interaction with the IMP, the investigator should report this to Novo Nordisk, e.g., in the alternative aetiology section on the safety information form.

children.name: P[369]
children.text: For the UK: Please see country-specific requirements in Appendix 11 (Section Error! Reference source not found.).

children.name: P[370]
children.text: The investigator will assess severity for each event reported during the study and assign it to one of the following categories:

children.name: LBody
children.text: Mild: A type of adverse event that is usually transient and may require only minimal treatment or therapeutic intervention. The event does not generally interfere with usual activities of daily living.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Moderate: A type of adverse event that is usually alleviated with additional specific therapeutic intervention. event interferes with usual activities of daily living, causing discomfort but poses no significant or permanent risk of harm to the research participant.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Severe: A type of adverse event that interrupts usual activities of daily living, or significantly affects clinical status, or may require intensive therapeutic intervention.  Note: An AE that is assessed as severe should not be confused with an SAE. Both AEs and SAEs can be assessed as severe.

children.name: P[371]
children.text: The investigator is obligated to assess the relationship between IMP and the occurrence of each AE/SAE. The investigator will use clinical judgment to determine the relationship.

children.name: P[372]
children.text: Relationship between an AE/SAE and the relevant IMP should be assessed as:

children.name: LBody
children.text: Probable - Good reason and sufficient documentation to assume a causal relationship.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Possible - A causal relationship is conceivable and cannot be dismissed.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Unlikely - The event is most likely related to aetiology other than the IMP.

children.name: P[373]
children.text: Alternative aetiology, such as underlying disease(s), concomitant medication and other risk factors, as well as the temporal relationship of the event to IMP administration, should be considered and investigated.

children.name: P[374]
children.text: The investigator should consult the current edition of the IB, when making the causality assessment. For each AE/SAE, the investigator must document in the medical records that he/she has reviewed the AE/SAE and has provided an assessment of causality.

children.name: P[375]
children.text: There may be situations in which an SAE has occurred, and the investigator has minimal information to include in the initial report. However, it is important that the investigator always makes an assessment of causality for every event before the initial transmission of the SAE data.

children.name: P[376]
children.text: The investigator may change his/her opinion of causality, in light of follow-up information, and update the causality assessment in the CRF.

children.name: P[377]
children.text: The causality assessment is one of the criteria used when determining regulatory reporting requirements.

children.name: P[378]
children.text: The investigator will select the most appropriate outcome that reflects the event outcome status at the time of reporting:

children.name: LBody
children.text: Recovered/resolved: The participant has fully recovered from the event, or by medical or surgical treatment the condition has returned to the level observed when first documented.

children.name: ParagraphSpan
children.text: Recovering/resolving: The condition is improving, and the participant is expected to recover from the event. This term may also be applicable for AEs ongoing at the time of death (where death is due to another AE).

children.name: P
children.text: Note: SAEs can be closed with the outcome ‘recovering/resolving’ only if the participant has withdrawn or completed the study, or end of study is near, and the investigator confirms that the participant is expected to fully recover from the event.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Recovered/resolved with sequelae: The participant has recovered from the event but with long-lasting or permanent effect(s) due to a disease, injury, treatment or procedure. If a sequela meets an SAE criterion, the AE must be reported as an SAE.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Not recovered/not resolved: The condition has not improved. This term may be applicable in cases of chronic conditions, cancer or AEs ongoing at time of death (where death is due to another AE).

children.name: LBody
children.text: Fatal: This term is only applicable if the participant died from a condition related to the reported AE. Outcomes of other reported AEs that occurred before the participant died should be assessed as ‘recovered/resolved’, ‘recovering/resolving’, ‘recovered/resolved with sequelae’ or ‘not recovered/not resolved’. An AE with a fatal outcome must be reported as an SAE.

children.name: P[379]
children.text: Note: AEs can be closed with the outcome ‘unknown’ only if the participant is lost to follow-up.

children.name: ParagraphSpan
children.text: The investigator is obligated to perform or arrange for the conduct of supplemental measurements and/or evaluations as medically indicated or as requested by Novo Nordisk to elucidate the nature

children.name: ParagraphSpan[2]
children.text: and/or causality of the AE or SAE as fully as possible (e.g., severe hypersensitivity reactions, Hy’s law). This may include additional laboratory tests or investigations, histopathological examinations, or consultation with other health care professionals.

children.name: P[381]
children.text: If a participant dies during participation in the study or during a recognised follow-up period, the investigator should, upon request, provide Novo Nordisk with the autopsy results including histopathology.

children.name: P[382]
children.text: New or updated information will be recorded in the CRF.

children.name: P[383]
children.text: The investigator will submit any updated SAE data to Novo Nordisk without undue delay, but not later than within 24 hours of receipt of the information.

children.name: P[384]
children.text: Relevant forms must be completed in the CRF.

children.name: P[385]
children.text: For SAEs, initial notification via telephone is acceptable, although it does not replace the need for the investigator to complete the AE forms and safety information forms within the designated reporting timelines (see Figure 9-2):

children.name: LBody

children.text: If the eCRF is unavailable for more than 24 hours, then the sites will use the paper backup AE form for SAE reporting, and if the eCRF is unavailable for more than 5 calendar days, then the site will use the paper backup safety information form. The information from the paper backup AE form and the safety information form will be entered in the eCRF as soon as it becomes available.

If a new SAE from a participant or updated information on a previously reported SAE needs to be reported after CRF decommission, a paper AE form and safety information form will be used to notify Novo Nordisk.

children.text: 9.10 Appendix 6: Technical complaints: Definition and procedures for recording, evaluation, follow-up and reporting

children.name: P[417]
children.text: A technical complaint is any written, electronic or oral communication that alleges inadequacy related to any of the following for a product (drug or device): identity, quality, labelling, durability, reliability, usability, safety, performance or malfunction.

children.name: P[418]
children.text: The technical complaint may be associated with an AE but does not concern the AE itself.

children.name: LBody
children.text: Problems with the physical or chemical appearance of study interventions (e.g., discoloration, particles or contamination).

children.name: LBody
children.text: Problems with packaging material including labelling.

children.text: Problems related to devices or the injection mechanism-activation or completion of injection, (to the pen-injector cap or needle).
