children.text: aSevere hypoglycaemia is an event requiring assistance of another person to actively administer carbohydrates, glucagon, or take other corrective actions. Plasma glucose concentrations may not be available during an event, but neurological recovery following the return of plasma glucose to normal is considered sufficient evidence that the event was induced by a low plasma glucose concentration.76

children.name: P[431]
children.text: Nocturnal hypoglycaemic episodes: episodes occurring between 00:01 and 05:59 both inclusive.

children.name: P[432]
children.text: Reporting of hypoglycaemic episodes by BG meters:

children.name: P[433]
children.text: Plasma glucose (PG) should always be recorded in the eDiary when a hypoglycaemic episode is suspected.

children.name: P[434]
children.text: When a participant experiences a hypoglycaemic episode, the participant should record the general information in relation to the hypoglycaemia (timing, PG measurements, symptoms, etc.) as described in the eDiary. The investigator should ensure correct reporting of the hypoglycaemic episode.

children.name: P[435]
children.text: If a participant is not able to fill in the eDiary at the time of the hypoglycaemic episode (e.g., in case of hospitalisation), the participant should report the episode in the eDiary retrospectively. The event leading to the delayed eDiary entry should be reported as an SAE  by the investigator, if applicable according to Appendix 3 (Section 9.7.3) by completing an AE form and a safety information form. One AE form and safety information form can cover several hypoglycaemic episodes if the participant has not recovered between the episodes, see Appendix 3 (Section 9.7.3).

children.name: P[436]
children.text: Upon onset of a hypoglycaemic episode the participant is recommended to measure PG every 15 minutes until the PG value is ≥3.9 mmol/L (70 mg/dL) and/or symptoms have been resolved in accordance with current guidelines.76

children.name: P[437]
children.text: Repeated PG measurements and/or symptoms will by default be considered as one hypoglycaemic episode until a succeeding PG value is ≥ 3.9 mmol/L (70 mg/dL) and/or symptoms have been resolved and should be reported as only one hypoglycaemic episode. In case of several low PG values within the hypoglycaemic episode, the lowest value is the one that will be reported as the PG value for the hypoglycaemic episode, but the start time of the episode will remain as the time for the first low PG value and/or symptom. The remaining values will be kept as source data.

children.name: P[438]
children.text: If the severity of a hypoglycaemic episode changes, only one hypoglycaemic episode will be reported, reflecting the most severe degree of hypoglycaemia.

children.name: P[439]
children.text: Regarding the question “could you help yourself?”, the investigator must instruct the participants to answer “No. I needed help and would not have managed on my own”, if the episode was an event that required assistance of another person to actively administer carbohydrate, glucagon, or take other corrective actions which the participants could not perform on their own, due to significant cognitive impairment. The investigator should verify the level 3 classification, i.e. that the participant had impaired cognitive function and was unable to recover independently during the episode. The investigator should document, in the visit notes or medical records, that they have confirmed the level 3 classification. If the hypoglycaemic episode has been incorrectly reported, the participant should be encouraged to correct this information in the eDiary, see ePID subsection within Section 8.  PG concentrations may not be available during an event, but neurological recovery following the return of PG to normal is considered sufficient evidence that the event was induced by a low PG concentration.76 eDiary review

children.name: P[440]
children.text: At each contact the investigator must review the eDiary data for correct reporting of PG values and hypoglycaemic episodes. In case of incomplete or incorrect data in the eDiary, the participant must be questioned whether there have been any severe hypoglycaemic episodes since the last visit and report accordingly. If notified of any severe (level 3) hypoglycaemic episode reporting in the eDiary, the investigator must review this data for potential SAEs within 7 days, see Section 9.7.5.

children.name: P[441]
children.text: The participant must be re-trained in how to report hypoglycaemic episodes if the investigator identifies low PG values not reported as hypoglycaemic episodes. The training should be documented by the investigator in source documents.

children.text: 9.12 Appendix 8: Titration guideline (for insulin treated patients)

children.name: P[442]
children.text: Titration guidelines have been developed, providing recommended dose adjustments at different PG levels to ensure that participants receive an optimal treatment. However, it is recognised that insulin treatment should be individualised, and the specific titration algorithms may not be applicable in certain clinical situations. Hence, it is important that other information, such as symptoms of hypo/hyperglycaemia, previous response to dose adjustments, other glucose measurements and other indicators of the participant’s level of glycaemic control, is taken into consideration when decisions on dosing are made. The investigator is responsible for the treatment of the participants and can therefore overrule the guidelines to avoid safety hazards.

children.name: H3[52]
children.text: Dose adjustment of basal insulin during the study

children.name: P[443]
children.text: After randomisation, adjustment of basal insulin should be considered weekly, based on prebreakfast SMPG measured for 3 consecutive days before each weekly contact (at site or by phone) by the Investigator throughout the treatment period, (see Section 8.3.8).

children.name: P[444]
children.text: Titration should be based on SMPG values obtained on the contact day and the two days prior to contact by the investigator. The adjustment should be done according to Table 9-5.

children.name: P[445]
children.text: If one or more SMPG values are missing, the adjustment should be performed based on the remaining SMPG values.

children.name: P[446]
children.text: If one of the SMPG values is below target (e.g., <4.0 mmol/L or 71 mg/dL), then the insulin dose should be reduced.

children.text: 9.14 Appendix 10: Mitigations to ensure participant safety and data integrity during a crisis

children.name: P[454]
children.text: A crisis is defined as a situation that causes substantial restrictions to study site access for participants and/or sponsor representatives.

children.name: P[455]
children.text: The mitigations mentioned in this appendix must only be used after approval by Novo Nordisk.

children.name: P[456]
children.text: According to local regulation, health authorities and independent ethics committees will be notified in case elements of the crisis appendix are activated.

children.name: P[457]
children.text: Sites should always try to follow the assessments outlined in the original SoA (Section 1.2) to the extent possible. Implementation of specific mitigations must be based on assessment of feasibility at the individual site.

children.name: P[458]
children.text: Sites must comply with local regulations, requirements and/or guidelines for the particular crisis if they are issued.

children.name: P[459]
children.text: Screening (V1), randomisation (V2) and visits 8, 19 and 21 must always be performed as on-site visits. If a site is unable to perform these visits on-site, screening and randomisation of new participants at that site must be on hold until on-site visits are possible.

children.name: P[460]
children.text: Visits 4, 5, 12 and 16 should be performed as on-site visits, if in any way possible. If not, assessments can be conducted remotely (video, phone or similar) or as home or off-site visits.

children.name: P[461]
children.text: On-site visits (Visits 6, 7, 10, 14 and 18) can be converted to remote visits (video, phone or similar) or home or off-site visits.

children.name: P[462]
children.text: If the end of intervention visit cannot be performed on-site, using remote (video, phone or similar) or home or off-site visits within the given visit window, the visit window for the assessment can be extended for up to 1 week for collection of PK and ADA samples.

children.name: P[463]
children.text: At each visit, the investigator must indicate in the CRF how the visit was performed and specify the reason for the preferred assessment method.

children.name: P[464]
children.text: If the visit cannot be completed within this window due to extenuating circumstances, Novo Nordisk will evaluate on a case-by-case basis.

children.name: P[465]
children.text: Assessments used for safety and the confirmatory estimands/endpoints (i.e., V2, V8, V19 and V21) must be prioritised. Specifications regarding how to perform these assessments using remote visits or as home visits will be provided by Novo Nordisk or the vendor.

children.name: P[466]
children.text: Local laboratories or diagnostic facilities can be used for haematology and biochemistry at the investigator’s discretion if on-site visits are not possible or in case of temporary lockdown of the central laboratory. Only findings meeting the definition for an AE (refer to Appendix 3 (Section 9.7)) are to be reported in the CRF.
